So let me slow it down because I don’t want you to miss a thing. 🐝 I can’t believe how much you guys loved the Chanticleer Garden video 🥹 It’s such a beautiful place and if you’re local to Philly I hope you add it to your summer bucket list. Should we plan a local garden club date?! 

If you’re not local, I feel so much privilege in being able to share the beautiful places in and around Philadelphia with you. Social Media gives us the opportunity to identify next places to visit but I hope that my videos and photos actually inspire you to get out and explore your own backyard. Even if the Reels trend is super fast video 😉 the best tip I can give for exploring a new place is to actually slow down. Turn each corner and turn around to see the view from a different perspective. Really get into your wanderlust! 

Happy long weekend friends 🥰

Embracing history in the City of Brotherly Love 🏛️🐍 

The iconic Join or Die flag, a powerful symbol of unity and resilience, reminds us of the extraordinary spirit and where we still need to go. There are 8 parts of the drawing, by Franklin, and it’s interesting to look at what colonies were account for together as one, such as New England and what states were omitted. Delaware for example, was included in PA in this drawing. 

Old City is surrounded by history!

Fun fact: one of the first times I came to Philly was on a train from out of state to register my daughter for school. It had to be in person. We were ready to move a few months later because my fiancé matched at Jefferson. That was a wild day and anyone who’s tried to get their kids into a school knows. 

I remember seeing this house for the first time that day. It’s around the corner from Washington Square Park. Turns out, they had already turned away many parents that day. Too many kids, not enough spots. We met an admin at the school who I shared my story with, why I couldn’t just come back tomorrow and where I traveled from. She was my first Philly Angel and the start of Philly and neighborhood love. 

This how is so beautiful and the quaint corner is something to stop and appreciate 🤎 #oldcitylove

Years before we moved to Philly it wasn’t even in the vision. I had lived in Boston for close to a decade. Swooning over Beacon Hill (living in Brighton) where brownstones and door knockers felt like a dream.

There is just something about a door knocker that’s so quaint and whimsical at the same time. 

When we moved to Philly into a 1760’s Henry Harrison rental, there were two sounds that delighted me like no other. One, was someone using the door knocker. We had a doorbell but really…what’s the fun in that?! The other was the mail slot being opened by the post person and the swoosh of the letters falling to the ground and onto the original wood floors. Theo would go running towards the door. 

I miss our rental in Old City 🤍 so many memories. 

#oldcitylove

Less than an hour out of the city is @longwoodgardens where if you love to get into the holiday spirit, you’ve got to venture out. 🌹 

Did you know that we are actually the garden capitol of America? How cool is that! @americasgardencapital so whether you love flowers and nature or you don’t, it’s absolutely worth a day or a half of day. Here are a few of my tips and preferences for visiting!

❄️ Unless you want to go at night to see the lights (which is also very cool), I suggest going as soon as they open. Literally be waiting at the door. You skip the crowds this way. Bonus points if you go on a week day. 
❄️ Entry and tickets are timed. Grab them online first and you can just have your QR code scanned for entry.
❄️ Leave time for the gift shop. Especially if you like plans and holiday decor.
❄️ they also often host a plant sale (hello, i mean, I’d love an orchid as a Christmas gift wouldn’t you?!) 
❄️ Longwood is kid friendly and they have a children’s garden with fountains. Kids 2-6 love it. With that said, they might also get bored the remainder of the time. I definitely plan to go back alone so I can geek out over the plants like the true nerd I am.
❄️ In most cases they don’t allow photo shoots. Read all the rules on photography before you go if you’re planning to whip out your tripod for a shoot with models, families, ect. 
❄️ No outside beverage is allowed. So while I prefer to look at plants with my @dunkin in hand from the roadtrip, I had to toss it. There is a cafe, think cafeteria food vibes but you know…it’s all a part of the experience.

What did I miss? Drop it in the comments to help others visiting for the first time. 

Xx Jenny #okdcitylove

The red door was “home” for 5 years ❤️

It was a beautiful trinity with 4 floors built in 1760 by Henry Harrison. Some of the floors were original, wood from ships that used to dock on the river. Harrison built these row homes for his daughter. Years later, an entire family at a time would live on each floor. 

Here are some fun facts about living here ❤️

* you can see Theo, my golden doodle that some days resembles Gritty, peeking through the window.
* I had my stroller stolen twice. Only twice yes, in 5 years by the same guy. You better believe I went and got my stroller back! Told him to cut that sh*t out! Mom life is hard enough 🤣 the next day he broke into a bridal shop, rearranged everything and left. Who remembers that!?
* the blue door and shutters are now dark green 
* my kitchen was in the basement! It was actually very cool but there were mice and I think I’m permanently scarred. 
* the best part were the neighbors. A true community. From leftovers to impromptu coffee dates, I really miss the neighborhood.

Now that I don’t live there anymore I can share in photos. It will always have a special place in my heart ❤️ 

#oldcitylove

Try it. Just try it ❤️ 

The other day I was sharing with someone why I started this account. I explained that before I moved here I had heard about the city in a negative light.

It was grey. It was gritty. It had crime. It wasn’t clean. You name it. ALL things that major US cities have. 

And then I got here and moved smack into the heart of Old City down an alley at Second and Market. I was over the moon with how many beautiful streets there were. The architecture. The artistic and creative spaces. The quaint coffee shops and bookstores. And the people! The people who would give you the shirt of their back if you needed it. 🫶🏼

So while some of those things are absolutely true. That’s not my Philly. MY Philly is seeing the beauty around the corner and I hope that by sharing it here, you’ll see it too. ❤️ #oldcitylove
